                            <comment id="16530732" author="daniel_sun" created="Tue, 3 Jul 2018 02:37:10 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Fixed by&#160;&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/apache/groovy/commit/371d8eb1eafbb4be8db21b2597044471d2886426&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/apache/groovy/commit/371d8eb1eafbb4be8db21b2597044471d2886426&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="16530906" author="daniel_sun" created="Tue, 3 Jul 2018 06:40:50 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;&quot;Long-lived processes (like an IDE) can run into stale class data as the type being compiled are continuously being edited/altered&quot;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;When the type being compiled are continuously being edited/altered, the reference of the type object will not be changed?&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;If the reference will be changed, long-lived processes (like an IDE) will not run into stale class data because the parameterized type cache compares references of objects via ==&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
